04103nam a22006255i 9780857450180DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20082008nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808574501807 a10.1515/97808574501802doi  a(DE-B1597)637249  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDD240 .B3389 2008 7aHIS0140002bisacsh04a943.086/21 aBeck, Hermann, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Fateful Alliance :bGerman Conservatives and Nazis in 1933: The ‹I›Machtergreifung‹/I› in a New Light /cHermann Beck. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (372 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tINTRODUCTION -- tChapter I PRAGMATISTS VERSUS FUNDAMENTALISTS The DNVP in the Weimar Republic, 1918–1933 -- tChapter II UNEASY PARTNERS The Relationship between the DNVP and the Nazis, 30 January–5 March -- tChapter III CONSERVATIVES AND THE NSDAP DURING THE “NATIONAL REVOLUTION” OF MARCH 1933 -- tChapter IV THE NAZIS AND THE CONSERVATIVE BÜRGERTUM A Clash of Worlds -- tChapter V BETWEEN THE DICTATES OF CONSCIENCE AND POLITICAL EXPEDIENCY The DNVP and Anti-Semitism -- tChapter VI REBELLION AGAINST THE INEVITABLE The Tribulations of Spring 1933 -- tChapter VII IGNOMINIOUS DEMISE Defections, Prohibitions, and Final Dissolution -- tEPILOGUE -- tAPPENDIX -- tSELECT BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn 30 January 1933, Alfred Hugenberg's conservative German National People's Party (DNVP) formed a coalition government with the Nazi Party, thus enabling Hitler to accede to the chancellorship. This book analyzes in detail the complicated relationship between Conservatives and Nazis and offers a re-interpretation of the Nazi seizure of power - the decisive months between 30 January and 14 July 1933. The Machtergreifung is characterized here as a period of all-pervasive violence and lawlessness with incessant conflicts between Nazis and German Nationals and Nazi attacks on the conservative Bürgertum, a far cry from the traditional depiction of the takeover as a relatively bloodless, virtually sterile assumption of power by one vast impersonal apparatus wresting control from another. The author scrutinizes the revolutionary character of the Nazi seizure of power, the Nazis' attacks on the conservative Bürgertum and its values, and National Socialism's co-optation of conservative symbols of state power to serve radically new goals, while addressing the issue of why the DNVP was complicit in this and paradoxically participated in eroding the foundations of its very own principles and bases of support.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aConservatismzGermanyxHistory. 0aNational socialism. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978085745018040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780857450180423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780857450180/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK